    <sharedstimuli>
        <sharedstimulus id="assets/d67a0fbc639faba52fe20/passage NEW.xml">
            <label key="829bbf2900f72bec6ff82736953c1761">
                <text>Pupil Reflex</text>
            </label>
            <label key="dc6aadb5e47a12a8212ed6fe924452cf">
                <text>The eyes and the brain receive and process light which allows people to see.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="22213f4d5f6a8ff3b7390adc99d243c5">
                <text>Light passes through the pupil of the eye (a hole in the centre of the iris that appears black). The light is changed to electrical signals by the retina at the back of the eye. These electrical signals are then sent to the brain, where they are interpreted.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="cf5a91f09b491430b478b009f94be791">
                <text>The pupil changes size in response to different levels of light, as shown in the diagram.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="8e5f5dc815d59bdadcf4bce06fc8a3e3">
                <text>
                    <strong>Bright light</strong>
                </text>
            </label>
            <label key="e12e8096757efb6a8579630c70ca03f6">
                <text>
                    <strong>Dim light</strong>
                </text>
            </label>
            <label key="f75c9af2f9523fcaa0c029651ffe814b">
                <text>iris</text>
            </label>
            <label key="34dae7e95f4f5c2097ac51202c8615b6">
                <text>small pupil</text>
            </label>
            <label key="80cbc709340d634e62702aaabe6f0cea">
                <text>large pupil</text>
            </label>
        </sharedstimulus>
    </sharedstimuli>
    <items>
        <item id="i639fac182b3b1171357983dead29109949">
            <label key="76b2d5d0cdc35e7d87bab46cc25d7479">
                <text>The reaction of the pupil to light is a type of reflex.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="66323e08e1853b5bbfede8e648107ccf">
                <text>Which one of the following descriptions best defines a reflex?</text>
            </label>
            <label key="c44c63b9955663571d72d813b901f4d5">
                <text>the conversion of light to electrical signals</text>
            </label>
            <label key="e0618d3a524b83ef6e2ba42c49d8c94e">
                <text>a fast and automatic response</text>
            </label>
            <label key="c03759780eff703703f0e474ff6b155e">
                <text>a response triggered by light</text>
            </label>
            <label key="c2a59ca7a6979f711e38a77cdb670ffc">
                <text>the transmission of signals to the brain</text>
            </label>
        </item>
        <item id="i639fac2de2cf417128ec47abd248636f5d">
            <label key="832cf327122ce6c3968fe62548c1cc36">
                <text>Some scientists think that pupil size increases when people are completing tasks that require more advanced thinking.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="a4ea7d834da33eed141f25f5c78721e5">
                <text>Which one of the following factors would be most important to control (keep constant) when testing this hypothesis?</text>
            </label>
            <label key="32b7e4caba0eba69e79cf08eb16007c8">
                <text> eye colour</text>
            </label>
            <label key="1ad0e372dc1e62ef9520c024559bc8dc">
                <text> type of thinking tasks</text>
            </label>
            <label key="1c7c94a463756544e5bbdb27f1f297f4">
                <text> the number of eyes tested</text>
            </label>
            <label key="12d7734d0fab19f79e0eee30cc0b52ed">
                <text> brightness of the room</text>
            </label>
        </item>
        <item id="i639fac36a9b68507179b66516e03ea3db0">
            <label key="00785847b2b691f4edb23cb84c4fbc75">
                <text>A cataract is an eye condition that reduces the amount of light that can pass through the eye.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="25162427081df2d9cd1143780f2b949c">
                <text>Which one of the following statements applies to people with cataracts?</text>
            </label>
            <label key="2a082bd65cb4c64db76b3baca09015de">
                <text> They have difficulty seeing at night.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="939c2632e102a1fb29e587000871be8a">
                <text> Wearing dark glasses improves their vision.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="4c713ff1e3652d8ed356aa7de84c0468">
                <text> They need dimmer-than-normal light to read or see objects.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="df8d2be7f00475699e4b15d8ee47fd55">
                <text> They have less need for protective eyewear such as sunglasses.</text>
            </label>
        </item>
        <item id="i639fac3b641ab1713974895b5345cbf266">
            <label key="8f4f6ce0b19be9e7425a25d4859cadcf">
                <text>Teo would like to research whether other factors affect pupil size.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="c91bcfe5d8c411b07227fcc1da5860d3">
                <text>The sources listed below are all potentially legitimate sources of information about factors affecting pupil size.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="b7f7481a6a7e3dbd1f0aaa313d38bd93">
                <text>Which one of the sources would provide the most reliable information for Teo’s research?</text>
            </label>
            <label key="7746b96dcca284b1e64e2bed970e046e">
                <text>a public speech from a medical doctor</text>
            </label>
            <label key="cedd1061b01b0be824228e520c357f54">
                <text>a scientific journal article published in 2019</text>
            </label>
            <label key="78843d573173285a2e565530e94c699b">
                <text>a social media post from a scientist</text>
            </label>
            <label key="f72795e133f5c00e192d0606cfaef35d">
                <text>a scientific report published in 1952</text>
            </label>
        </item>
    </items>
